If you find yourself stuck in a 9 to 5 job that you absolutely despise, it's time to start thinking about how to transition into something that brings you fulfillment and joy. Here is a four-step process you can use. 

Step 1: Self-Assessment

Take the time to reflect on what makes you happy, what you're passionate about, and what skills you possess. Start by creating a list of things you enjoy doing, whether it's a hobby, volunteering, or work-related task. Then, research careers that match your interests and values. Use online resources and informational interviews to learn more about your desired industries and positions. I love the Wealth Building and Dynamics test online. 

Step 2: Developing Your Skills

Once you've identified potential career paths, start building the necessary skills and experience. This can mean taking courses, volunteering in related organizations, or freelancing to gain hands-on experience. Invest in yourself and your development, and don't forget to network with professionals in the positions or industries that you're interested in.

Step 3: Creating a Transition Plan

Leaving one job for another can be financially challenging. Develop a transition plan to help you financially, emotionally, and mentally. This can include building up your savings, reducing your expenses, seeking part-time work or financial support, and building a support system of friends or mentors. Create a realistic timeline for your transition and start implementing your plan as soon as possible.

Step 4: Taking The Leap

Once you've built the skills, gained experience, and created a transition plan, it's time to take the leap. Know that leaving a job you hate to pursue your dream career is a brave and worthwhile decision. Practice self-care, stay motivated, and remember that setbacks and challenges are a part of the journey.

Implementing a self-assessment, building skills, creating a transition plan, and taking the leap are key steps to achieving career fulfillment. Remember to be patient, persistent, and positive in your approach to career change. Or becoming a boss!

🥑 Avocado oil has become more popular and an alternative healthy oil swap for toxic and unhealthy vegetable & seed oils 
It has been popping up more and more in “healthier” processed foods like salad dressings, mayonnaise and various sauces. 

But is it really as healthy as we think?  Researchers found that the majority of avocado oil sold in the U.S is either labeled incorrectly, rancid or mixed with other oils.  Some samples that were labeled “pure” or “extra- virgin” avocado oil, tested for 100% soybean oil.  Many samples didn’t contain any avocado oil. 

Of 22 avocado oil samples tested, 15 had been oxidized before the expiration date and 6 had been mixed with large amounts of either safflower, sunflower or soybean oil.  Only 2 samples were pure and non oxidized.

The problem is that currently, there are no regulations for testing the quality and purity of avocado oil so companies are getting away with false labeling and advertising. 
So how do you know if your avocado oil is pure and not rancid?

Pure avocado oil has a green hue and has (to no surprise) a mild avocado/earthy taste. Trust your taste buds and your nose.  Rancid oil will taste bad and smell off. 

Chosen Foods and Marianne’s Avocado oil were samples that tested pure and non oxidized. Stick with these brands or other sources of fat like raw and grass fed butter, ghee, coconut oil, tallow and olive oil.
